Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:38 Defendant Timothy A Shaw in court with attorney Harry R Hertel.  Craig Lambert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  

Blake Borchardt is sworn as a witness.  Testifies to his employment with Marshfield Police Dept.  Testifies to dispatch to S Maple Dr in Marshfield on 08/23/2014 and contact with Christina Geiger regarding sexual assault of MMR.  Testifies to contact he had with Veronica Shaw and with Tiana.  Describes what Tiana witnessed.  Veronica pointed out Tim Shaw.  Identifies Tim Shaw in the courtroom.  Testifies to contact with Tim Shaw and observations made.  Testifies to what Mia stated about the occurance.  All 3 girls indicated that they had been drinking that night and that Tim Shaw obtained the alcohol.  

Atty Hertel cross examines the witness.  Reviewed crime lab reports before testifying today.   Testifies to notes he reviewed prior to testifying today.
